		<h4>Week 36</h4>
		<p><b>Baby : </b>Growth will slow down in coming weeks both so your baby will be able to fit through the narrow passage way to the outside and so he or she can store up all the energy needed for the delivery. By now your baby will at least make you realise 10 to 12 times a day that he is active not just by gentle movement inside your womb but by blow on your liver or ribs or bladder.</p>
		<p>When you are 36 weeks pregnant your baby skull bones are not fused together yet so the head can easily ( well relatively) easily maneuver through the birth canal. Your baby's skull is not the only soft structure in a little body. Most of a bones and cartilage are quite soft as well allowing for an easier journey into the world during delivery. But don't worry I will Harden for the first few years of a life.</p>
		<p>By now many of your baby systems are pretty mature, at least in baby terms and just about ready for life on the outside. Blood circulation for instance has been perfected and your baby's immune system has developed enough to protect your little one from infections outside the womb. Others however still need a few finishing touches. One such notable example is digestion which actually won't be fully mature until sometime after birth. Why? Inside her little gestational cucoon your baby has relied on the umbilical cord for nutrition meaning the digestive system though developed, hasn't been operational. It will take the first year or two to bring it up to the speed.</p>
		<p>in the preparation of labour babies adrenal gland turns on. It releases hormones  that causes the uterine contraction. It means baby decides for himself when to arrive in this world.</p>

		<p><b>Mother : </b> Welcome to your last month of pregnancy. It is a good thing your baby's is almost done cooking since your body me feel pretty done by now to. For one thing by 36 weeks pregnant you are doing the penguin waddle many third trimester mums to be adopt. The new walk is not in your imagination. It's in your connective tissue which those hormones are loosening and softening. And that's particularly important now that you are nearing your due date. You'r baby who is grown quite large by this point needs to fit through your pelvic bones so it's good that they are more flexible at this stage it's your body's way of getting ready to squeeze a big baby out of a small space.</p>
		<p>The downside to all this joint flexibility, besides the resemblance you now bear to your feathered friends, is pelvic pain. And the pressure from your baby's head but deeper and deeper in your pelvis in your heavier you trust weighing you down, and it's no wonder it's a pain to walk around these days. To relieve the discomfort, relax with your hips elevated, do some pelvic exercises, take warm baths, apply warm compress. Get a prenatal massage from certified therapist or try some complementary and alternative therapies. A belly sling may be helpful.</p>
		<p>There is a happy upshot, believe it or not. As a baby drops into your pelvic cavity - and keep in mind that not all baby drop before labor begins -  the upward pressure of uterus on your daiphragm is relieved. Once this lightning as it's known in the pregnancy strikes you will be able to take bigger and deeper breaths. Your stomach also won't be so squished anymore making eating a full meal more comfortable.</p>
		<p>Keep in mind the labour not always follows your ideal scenario. It's mandatory to have a positive mindset and flexibility for all the possible ways to deliver your healthy baby. Trust your doctor whatever decision they will take.</p>
		<p><b>Tips</b></p>
		<p><b>Note movement changes : </b>Don't be alarmed if your baby's movements have changed from  gentle moves to hard kicks. He has less room for the movements. You still keep track of your baby's movement everyday, do don't be stressed.  Try sipping a sugary beverage and see if your baby moves and be sure to call your doctor if there is any decrease in fetal movement or an unusual change in the pattern of baby's movement.</p>
		<p><b>Get plenty of B6 : </b>it's a good idea to change your protein with an adequate supply of pyridoxine it is known as vitamin b6 and it is very helpful and its function is to help your body and baby use all the protein to do this cell building job.</p>
		<p>You will find b6 in prenatal vitamins and also in bananas , brown rice ,bran ,Soya beans, oatmeals, potatoes, tomatoes, spinach, watermelon and meat. See there is overlap  in the protein source making a job even easier.</p>
		<p><b>Ask your pre labor signs : </b>If you feel uncomfortable and are concerned about any prelabour or pregnancy symptoms,  it's always best to call your healthcare provider. You might make a trip to hospital or doctors office that turns out to be unnecessary but you would be far far from the only mom-to-be who's done. So pre labor can last for a few hours or months or more and signs and symptoms can be different for every person.</p>
		<p><b>pack your hospital bag : </b>Delivery day is getting close to its time to pack your hospital bag if you haven't already.</p>

