		<h4>Week 37</h4>
		<p><b>Baby : </b>By now your baby is fully grown to survive on its own. Usually by this time the baby acquires the position that is the head is lying just over the pelvis so that it can pass easily through birth canal. Technically before 37 completed weeks The baby is usually quoted as early term.</p>
		<p>The lungs are nature but not functional yet once the baby is delivered and take its first breath they will start functioning.</p>
		<p>The babies starts preparing for the first breath by simulating the inhaling and exhaling mechanism by drinking or swallowing the amniotic fluid. Part of it is filtered through urine and the remnants like hair, vernix, lanugo are are turned in the form of meconium.</p>
		<p>This meconium is thick like dark and it is excreted in first few weeks of birth. The babies are already having lactobacillus and E- coli which helps them to digest the mother's milk as well as boost their digestive immunity to prevent them from the infections.</p>
		<p>Some of the internal organs a are still developing like some neuronal layers of brain are still developing also the bones and cartilage starts to Harden except that of the skull bone. The wakefulness and sleep cycles are recognisable at this time in the baby and will remain so for few weeks after the birth.</p>
		<p><b>Mother : </b>At 37 weeks pregnant your baby's lungs are likely mature but that doesn't mean he's finished growing yet. In fact until the end of week 38 is technically considered an early term and he's  still packing on about 200grams per day or a kg a week. At this age the average foetus weighs about 2.5 kg.</p>
		<p>it's anyone's guess when your baby will decide to make his appearance will he be sociably early fashionably late or write on time but that doesn't stop your practitioner from guessing when labor will begin Just what is your doctor looking for first for dilutation or how far your cervix has opened specifically your service needs to open to 10 cm for the baby to pass through  the bird canal.</p>
		<p>There will be few noticeable changes in your body like your uterus riding down. More and More digestive upset and frequent urination because now uterus will create more pressure over your bladder and intestine  as it descends.</p>
		<p>Your breasts are also now preparing for lactation. You may start leaking colostrum, a thick yellow fluid from your breasts. Don't try to express the milk by pressing the nipples because it may elicit the labour due to release of oxytocin in your body. Just keep the breast clean and use nursing pads if needed.</p>
		<p>Right now your tiny  superstar is rehearsing for his big debut simulating breathing by inhaling and exhaling amniotic fluid, sucking his thumb blinking and pivoting from side to side. One day you feel his bottom on the left side the next its flipped around to the right!</p>
		<p><b>Tips</b></p>
		<p><b>finish your baby's nursery : </b>Less than 5% of babies deliver on the due date. So don't assume you have three weeks to finish your to do list but don't go crazy either.</p>
		<p><b>slow weight gain : </b>Not gaining a kg in a week is normal. Many women don't give any wet at all during the last month but the child keeps on growing.</p>
		<p><b>stay hydrated : </b>Feeling bloated don't stop drinking water drinking the recommended 8 glass will actually help ease your fluid retention.</p>
		<p><b>Get an exercise ball : </b>an exercise ball is safe and effective tool for strengthening your core muscles during pregnancy choose a high quality ball made from best resistant material and be short to inflate it to the correct size for your height. 22 inches (55 centimetres) for women shorter than 5 foot 3, and 26 inches (65 centimeters) tall women.</p>
		<p><b>stay sane while you rest : </b>Trying to establish a routine even if the highlight is a soak in a tepid tub, followed by a nap or a morning on the couch followed by an afternoon in the bed.</p>
		<p>You will feel a little better if you give the day some sort of structure and it's perfectly ok if your routine involves multiple viewings of your favourite show.</p>
		<p><b>choosing a labor support person : </b> Nowadays patients are given a choice to choose a person to support them in the labour process usually it is the person who will provide her with moral support and emotional support. Often the companion is husband or a mother or a friend. It is very important for the support person to be mentally strong and emotionally strong because if they will become anxious or nervous about the happenings going in the labour room they might create more tension that makes the doctor and the staff more uncomfortable.</p>

