		<h4>Week 39</h4>
		<p><b>baby : </b>Chubby cheeks, dimple chin, Rosy lips, NO teeth within. At 39 weeks pregnant I have got what is officially considered a full term baby.</p>
		<p>Those measurements won't change much from now but his brain is still growing at an astonishing rate - a pace that will continue for the first three years of life - with changes you will be able to recognise first and as your baby's skill packed bag of tricks expand almost daily.</p>
		<p>which 39 is for working  on sensory processing, reflexes and spinal column. two of the reflexes sucking and grasping reflexes are ready to go and dozen  more of of involuntary reflexes and conditioned responses will appear after birth.</p>
		<p>Their lungs are ready to expand and intestines are ready to function. The digestive tract is so well developed that it will be able to digest the highly nutritious collustrum from from now onwards</p>
		<p>Heard that babies cry a lot? there is definitely truth to that rumour - as you'll find out soon enough usually in the middle of the night but what you may not have heard that tiny babies don't produce tiny tears   when they cry since their tear ducts aren't fully open for business. </p>
		<p>Small babies have layers of fat around major vessels , internal organs and rib cage, this pad of fat helps them to regulate the body temperature. As the baby grows this set will slowly disappear.</p>

		<p><b>mother : </b>The end and a whole new beginning! - is inside at 39 weeks pregnant. You are probably feeling increasingly uncomfortable by now as you lug around your ever heavier uterus and its contents plus your pelvis is feeling achier and achier as your baby bears down. Braxton Hicks contractions are likely increasing in strength and frequency and that's a good sign since it means your body is gearing up for the big event. Finding a comfortable way to sit down or stand or lie down takes to go through several different positions. Mothers feel scared to sit down thinking that it might hurt the baby which is wrong, the pelvis protects the baby very well.</p>
		<p>Your appetite is changing now and small frequent meals which you use to take to avoid heartburn are no more needed as you feel more relaxed because your baby has now descended into your pelvis. You can eat your meal fully. Avoid eating baked foods, sweetsand heavy fried items.</p>
		<p>At 39 weeks you may find that you are dropping your weight by 1-2 kgs and that is because your body is preparing itself for the process of delivery by eliminating excesd water and anything else which may come into the way of labour. The hormones which initiate uterine contractions also have such effect on intestine and you will feel to purge.</p>
		<p>signs of Labor-Knowing that you can go any day you should be watching out for signs of labour. This include the rupture of the membranes or water breaking that contain amniotic fluid, diarrhoea or nausea which many women experience just before the onset of labour. spurts of energy also known as nesting Instinct, the loss of mucus plug that seals the opening of the uterus and bloody shaw which arise when your capillaries rupture from the dilatation and effacement of your cervix causing any discharge to appear pink or red tinged. Once you have seen bloody shaw labor is probably just a day or two away, so don't try to set your watch to it since it's not a definitive time table, just make sure your bags packed.</p>

		<p><b>Tips</b></p>
		<p><b>stages of labor : </b>For most of the women, labour is the most intense experience of their life. Being informed about the different stages of labor helps a woman to prepare their mind and strengthen their psychology and such women who are mentally prepared and psychologically strong are seen to have less difficulty during the course of natural labor pains.</p>
		<p><b>There are four stages of labor : </b>The first stage of labour is the beginning of contractions. These contractions are accompanied by dilatation and effacement of cervix and gradually when the contraction increases in frequency and duration the baby glides down the pelvis.</p>
		<p>The second stage of labour is from full dilatation of cervix till the delivery of your baby. In this stage the intensity of labour pain is much increased and becomes a sort of unbearable  intensity. Mother feels a natural urge to push down the baby these are known as bearing down efforts. Just as the baby is delivered there will be a sudden moment of relaxation felt by the mother. To make the most of it take a deep breath hold it in and try to push at the right place, don't push throug your face, legs and don't scream. Open up as much as possible and in between pushes  take a few deep breaths, relax and get recharge for the next big push.</p>
		<p>Finally your  baby emerges,  these few moments are giving a mother an unparalleled sense of euphoria. nurse will put the baby on your abdomen to have a skin to skin contact and the assistance staff or doctor will cut the umbilical cord. your baby will start crying now.</p>
		<p>the baby will be handed over to the pediatrician and now the  the third stage of labor begins.</p>
		<p>in this stage the doctor will deliver your placenta and will clean uterus of any after births . After giving you local anaesthesia your episiotomy stitches will be taken.</p>
		<p>In 4th stage of labour you will be under watchful eye that your blood pressure is maintaining you are not going through any unnecessary bleeding. Is your baby feeding well and the vaccination of your baby,  all these will be covered in this two hours after the birth.</p>
		<p>You should start feeding the baby within half an hour of birth because this will not only help the baby to get adapted to the new mechanism of procuring food but it will help to contract the uterus as well.</p>

