		<h4>Week 40</h4>
		<p><b>Baby : </b> This is the moment you and your baby have been waiting for. At 40 weeks pregnant you are at official end of your pregnancy. Your baby probably ways anywhere between 2.2 to 2.8 to 3 kgs and measures between 19 to 22 inches. Hundreds of perfectly healthy babies are born smaller or bigger.</p>
		<p>your baby is as excited as ever to meet the outside world. His body and sense organs are now fully developed and in sonography your doctor might show you, that your baby is now playing inside your uterus with umbilical cord, holding it like a guitar or sucking his or her thumb. These all are his preparation or you can say rehearsal going in utero so that as soon as the baby is born the baby can latch to your breast and suck in the breast milk. The suckling and grasping reflex are present in your baby.</p>
		<p>Soon after birth the babies are very cranky because from the darkness and warmth of mothers womb,  the baby is suddenly into noisy and bright atmosphere. For him the outside atmosphere is hostile for a while so he will cry and let him cry that will indeed help his lung to expand.</p>
		<p>Also the first milk is often yellowish, thick and comes as few drops, it is known as colostrum. This colostrum is very rich in  antibodies and antitoxins. It prevents baby against infections as well as it helps digestive tract of baby to get adapted to the milk. It is produced in last few weeks of pregnancy and first few days after baby's birth every mother should feed the colostrum to the baby.</p>
		<p>From your baby's perspective you will look a bit blurry-- at birth baby Central vision is still developing. Its ok to say hello to your new arrival. Your baby will very likely recognise the sound of your voice and your partners .</p>
		<p>you will notice  that your little one is still curled in fetal position and that's because it's the only position she or he has really known. Its a comforting one to be in that's also why so many newborns like to be swaddled. It reminds them of your uterus. It will take some time for them to realise that they have room to spread out.</p>

		<p><b>mother : </b>Few more days of anxious waiting and the exciting and challenging time of labour is soon to start. when will your body know it's time to deliver this baby. Just because your due date is marked on a calendar doesn't mean mother nature's gotten the memo.</p>
 		<p>About 30% off all pregnancy last's longer than 40 weeks and it's anyone's guess when your might end. Thankfully your practitioner probably won't let it go longer than 41 weeks.By now you have no doubt lost a night or two's sleep over when and where it will happen.</p>
 		<p>One event that's not guaranteed before the onset of labour is your water breaking the rupture of amniotic sac surrounding your baby the last 9 months. first few more than 15% of women experience a rupture of membranes before liver begins and second if your water does break in public is less likely to come as a torrent shall tidal wave and more likely to come as a slow  circle or small gush. One thing you can be pretty sure of if your water breaks before your contractions have started labour will likely begin in earnest within 24 hours either that or your practitioner will start it for you within 24 hours.</p>
 		<p>Your water actually breaks when you are in labour either the cervix is fully dilated or cervix is not open that is premature rupture of membranes or else it will happen in first stage of labour. When yourwater break suddenly trying noticing the colour and order of it and the time of it and inform your practioner. If it's green ,brown or black you need to go to hospital immediately.</p>
 		<p>mucus plug that closes your cervix actually escapes out in the form of mucoid that is of egg white consistency, It may be mixed with blood giving it a colour of tan brown or pink or even sometimes red. Usually labour starts 2-3 days after expulsion of this mucus plug. It may come out while you are in toilet or taking bath or you might see it as a stain on your undergarments.</p>
 		<p><b>Tips, Ask about inducing the labour</b></p>
 		<p>talk to your practitioner about when, why and how he or she might want to induce the labour. Unless there are health and medical reasons to induce, it's typically not recommended before 40 completed weeks of pregnancy.</p>
 		<p><b>Shave safely : </b>feeling a little extra for furry these days? you can choose an option of waxing or shaving your legs and private parts but it is advisable to take help of some other person, because you might not be able to see beyond your belly and your balance might not be good. better to find a friend to do that for you.</p>
 		<p><b>Add iron : </b>In case you haven't heard labour takes endurance - and lots of it. To make sure you are the little labouring engine that could( and can) you will need to make sure your iron intake is up to the mark and iron deficiency can cause extra fatigue, something you don't want to take into the birthing room with you. Go on eating a little handful more of peas,  the green veggies iron fortified cereals, dry fruits, nuts and whole wheat bread and if you are eating non veg you can go for red meat. Eat your extra iron supplement which you should still be taking together with the vitamin c and calcium source for better absorption.</p>
 		<p><b>go for a soak! : </b> defy gravity and give your body a break from all the extra weight by floating in a warm bath or pool, avoid the hot tub though.!</p>
 		<p><b>do a mini workout! : </b>Turn from side to side, slowly twisting at the waist, letting your arm swing freely (being careful not to whack anyone). You can also clench your butt and hold for count of two then release. Try to do15 or 20 arm swings and but clenches-  it will make time pass and tone your muscles too.</p>
 		<p><b>keep busy : </b>Baby on the brain? it's hard to think of anything else when your due date has come near. Take a walk (which might even help get your contractions going), spend some time focusing on self care, you may not have the chance (once baby is on board). Watch a movie or two. Tell your friends and family to stop calling everyday, remind them that no news is  ......no news.</p>
 		<p><b>stay relaxed : </b>Of course you are as excited and nervous as can be, but it's important to try to relax atmost as you can during the first phase of labour will need to save your strength for later on.</p>
 		<p>You can also try taking a walk which might even kick up the contractions a notch.  eat little snake if your hungry but avoid fatty foods and don't overeat.</p>
 		<p> don't worry about obsessively timing contractions at this point will just get bored and frustrated but to check periodically to see whether there are getting closer together.</p>
 		<p> lastly make sure you use the bathroom as full bladder can get in the way of labour.</p>
